The **Sharpe ratio** refers to the numerical assessment that allows investors to measure the returns with consideration to the given risks. It can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Sharpe ratio}&=\dfrac{\text{E}(\text{Asset return}-\text{Risk-free return})}{\sigma}
\end{aligned}$$

Where,

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{E}&=\text{Expected value}\\
\sigma&=\text{Standard deviation}
\end{aligned}$$

In order to solve for the Sharpe ratio of the company stock, we will use $E=17\%$ as stated in the problem. Moreover, in this case, we will sue the risk free return average of the treasury bills found in Table 12.4 which is $3.4\%$. Finally, the standard deviation given for the company stocks is $10.99\%$. Substituting these, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Sharpe ratio}&=\dfrac{17(3.56-3.4)}{10.99}
\end{aligned}$$
